\title{The foundation and axiomatics of the library}

\import{stt-macros}

\p{We use the \strong{non-cubical} variant of Agda for formalisation in this
library. Whilst this doesn't correspond precisely to any known fragment type theory,
this roughly corresponds to plain Martin–Löf type theory with indexed-inductive
types.}

\p{The \code{Foundations} namespace falls most rigidly into this framework, with
additional axioms such as [function extensionality](Foundations.FunExt) being
explicitly included in the hypotheses when they are needed. In the foundational
modules we also make use of the following inductive types:

\ul{
  \li{The [identity types](identity-def) (using the \em{based}, or Paulin-Mohring style)}
  \li{The [natural numbers](Foundations.Nat) and the [truncation levels](Foundations.TruncationLevels), which are just
notationally shifted natural numbers}
  \li{The [integers](Foundations.Int)}
  \li{The [booleans](Foundations.Bool)}
  \li{The [empty type](Foundations.Empty)}
  \li{[Binary coproducts](Foundations.Coproducts)}
  \li{The [finite types](Foundations.Fin) as an indexed-inductive family of types}
}}

\subtree[tot-0233]{
\title{Higher inductive types}

\p{In \ref{Axioms.CanonicalPushouts}, we postulate the existence of pushouts, together
with [rewrite rules]() that makes the eliminator computes on point constructors.
We use pushouts to derive other "\em{non-recursive}" higher inductive types,
such as [coequalisers](Core.Coequalisers),
[sequential colimits](Core.CanonicalSequentialColimits), and [joins](Core.Joins).
These inherit the computational behaviour of pushouts. We also use pushouts to
formalise [[egbertrijke]]'s join construction, which yields [type theoretic
replacement](stt-00HY).}


\p{In addition to the above, we postulate the existence of a non-recursive
higher inductive type, namely the
[localisation operator](Axioms.FreeAlgebraicInjective) as presented by
Rijke–Shulman–Spitters \citek{RSS20}. This is quite a general construction
that allows us to construct [localisations](Modalities.Instances.Localisation)
for any accessible subuniverse.
}
}

\p{In contrast to the \code{Foundations} namespace, the modules within the
\code{Core} namespace freely use function extensionality, the existence of pushouts
and univalence. We say that these formalisations are carried out "in
\em{univalent foundations}".}

\p{In the \code{Modalities.Cohesion} namespace, we also use the [cohesive type
theory]() capabilities of Agda.}

\p{In the \code{Synthetic} namespace we do not postulate any further axioms aside
from those given above. When further axioms are needed, we instead assume them as
additional parameters–to a given module or individual definition. As a general rule
we aim to organise the library to use the minimal amount of assumptions needed for
any given theorem. This furthers our understanding and makes the lemmas more broadly
applicable.}
